title: Senior PeopleSoft ELM Consultant
description: Enterprise Learning Management 9.1: Responsible for testing ELM 9.1 to verify that the product met current client needs; also responsible for pointing out key differences between versions 9.1 and 9.1; some delivered aspects of 9.1 replaced the need for client customizations to version 9.0 while other changes removed the needs for customizations currently in place. Enterprise Learning Management 9.0: Performed Fit/Gap Analysis of ELM 9.0 to current client needs. Led the testing efforts for 9.0 including selecting the teams for testing and dividing the responsibilities of testing areas amongst the team members; advised on the web-based training aspects for the end-users (including modifying and editing the training products). Created customization specs, advised on customizations, their design and approaches, and demonstrated AppPackage modification approaches to the technical team. Performed both client and end-user training on the product (training efforts covered both basic product knowledge and problem solving skills). Performed advanced end-user training (including the creation of exercises specifically written to develop proficiency with the input of training into ELM 9.0 and to demonstrate the flow of data through the system—i.e. how various data in the product related to each other at different stages). Developed a Policy and Procedures document to regulate use of ELM 9.0 for the end-users.

title: Senior Programmer
description: A key member of team of programmers that gathered requirements for the U.S. Army’s business process for the Army Training Requirements and Resources System (ATTRS) on the DIMHRS Project while instituting solutions for the Army’s future environment. Worked to institute the Federal Enterprise Architecture (FEA) Framework by determining business drivers for the current fragmented military training systems. Worked to understand and plot out the current training architecture in order to relay this information the senior management. Created plans to transition from the current state to the desired future state of training by instituting a single Learning Management System (LMS) that would be rolled out across the various branches of the military. Employing a single LMS was to save federal dollars by consolidating training records into one LMS, thereby reducing the number training systems that needed to be maintained individually and increase the ease with which training information could be shared across branches. Responsibilities included: • Designing and implementing custom modifications and system processes for the new environment, PeopleSoft Enterprise Learning Management v. 8.81. • Designing and building custom PeopleSoft fields, records, pages, PeopleCode and components using PeopleTools 8.44. • Installing PeopleSoft 8 Standalone versions. • Utilizing the Application Engine, (including SQL and PeopleCode) to construct custom batch programs. • Manipulating data through the back-end using SQL. • Devising and delivering presentations to senior level management as well as federal clients. • Performing Fit/Gap Analysis and Requirements Gathering for the Army Training Requirements and Resources System (ATTRS) on the DIMHRS (Defense Integrated Military Human Resources System) Project. • Developing Business Process Re-engineering (BPR) options for the future systems after performing detailed business process analysis of the current system.
name: Christian Xavier

groups.name: North Dallas Chapter - The Professional Forum
